Here's a clean approach using **merged `ResourceDictionary` swapping**:

### 1. Define each theme as a separate ResourceDictionary

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#E0E0E0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#4CC2FF</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

### 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always last)
        if (mergedDicts.LastOrDefault() is { } current)
            mergedDicts.Remove(current);

        ResourceDictionary next = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new Themes.LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(next);

        // Persist choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

### 3. Seed a default theme in `App.xaml.cs`

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
}
```

### 4. Use `DynamicResource` everywhere

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" Text="Hello" />
</ContentPage>
```

> **Key:** `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) is what makes the UI update immediately when the dictionary is swapped.

### 5. Wire up the settings page

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object? s, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is AppTheme selected)
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(selected);
}
```

### Quick summary

| Piece | Role |
|---|---|
| One `ResourceDictionary` per theme | Holds colors, styles, brushes |
| `ThemeService.ApplyTheme` | Swaps the dictionary + persists with `Preferences` |
| `DynamicResource` bindings | Picks up new values instantly |
| `LoadSavedTheme()` in `App()` | Restores choice on launch |

This pattern scales well — you can add `Style` objects and custom brushes to each theme dictionary as your brand grows.
